{"title_page": "Gotland", "text_new": "{{short description|Island and historical province in Sweden}}\n{{hatnote|Not to be confused with [[G\u00f6taland]]. For other uses, see [[Gotland (disambiguation)]] and [[Gothland (disambiguation)]]}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox islands\n| name             = Gotland<br />Gutland&nbsp;{{small|([[Gutnish language|Gutnish]])}}\n| image_name       = Gotland vapen.svg\n| image_caption    = Coat of arms\n| image_size       = 100px\n| map_image        = Sweden Gotland location map modified.svg\n| map_caption      = Gotland (Sweden)\n| native_name      =\n| native_name_link =\n| nickname         =\n| location         = [[Baltic Sea]]\n| coordinates      = {{Coord|57|30|N|18|33|E|region:SE_type:isle_scale:2500000|display=inline,title}}\n| archipelago      = Slite archipelago\n| total_islands    = 14 large + a number of smaller\n| major_islands    = Gotland, [[F\u00e5r\u00f6]], [[Gotska Sand\u00f6n]], [[Stora Karls\u00f6]], [[Lilla Karls\u00f6]], [[Furillen]]\n| area_km2         = 3,183.7\n| length_km        = 176\n| width_km         = 52\n| coastline_km     = 800\n| coastline_footnotes = &nbsp;(including F\u00e5r\u00f6)\n| highest_mount    = Lojsta hed\n| elevation_m      = 82\n| country          = [[Sweden]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title     = County\n| country_admin_divisions           = [[Gotland County]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_1   = Municipality\n| country_admin_divisions_1         = [[Gotland Municipality]]\n| country_largest_city              = [[Visby]]\n| country_largest_city_population   = 23,600<ref name=\"Gotlandisiffror\" />\n| population       = 58,595<ref name=\"population\" />\n| population_as_of = 2017\n| density_km2      = 18.4\n| ethnic_groups    =\n| additional_info  =\n| module = \n{{Designation list\n| embed = yes\n| designation1 = Ramsar\n| designation1_offname = Gotland, east coast\n| designation1_date = 5 December 1974\n| designation1_number = 21<ref>{{Cite web|title=Gotland, east coast|website=[[Ramsar Convention|Ramsar]] Sites Information Service|url=https://rsis.ramsar.org/ris/21|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>}}\n}}\n\n'''Gotland''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0261|\u0252|t|l|\u0259|n|d}}; {{IPA-sv|\u02c8\u0261\u0254\u030ct\u02d0land|lang|sv-Gotland.ogg}};<ref>[http://sok.saol.se/pages/P296_M.jpg] [[Svenska Akademiens ordlista]], 6 February 2013</ref> older spellings include '''Gottland''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0261|\u0252|t|l|\u0259|n|d}} or '''Gothland''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0261|\u0252|\u03b8|l|\u0259|n|d}};<ref>[http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/gotland]</ref> ''Gutland'' in the [[Gutnish|local dialect]])<ref>{{cite web|title=Namnet Gotland|trans-title=The name Gotland|url=http://www.guteinfo.com/?id=1890|website=www.guteinfo.com|publisher=Guteinfo|accessdate=7 April 2015}}</ref> is Sweden's largest [[island]].<ref name=\"Renate\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AyIU6XIeDKwC&pg=PA178 |title=The Baltic Sea: new developments in national policies and international cooperation, Volume 1 |authors=Renate Platz\u00f6der, Philom\u00e8ne A. Verlaan |publisher=Martinus Nijhoff Publishers |year=1996}}</ref><ref name=\"Sailing\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T7-G4MRcvjwC&pg=PA147 |title=Sailing Directions, Baltic Sea |publisher=ProStar Publications |isbn=978-1-57785-759-4}}</ref><ref name=\"Knowles\">{{cite book |last=Knowles |first=Heather |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z25SYOLd_pIC&lpg=PA145&dq=%22the%20largest%20island%20in%20the%20baltic%20sea%22&pg=PA145#v=onepage&q=%22the%20largest%20island%20in%20the%20baltic%20sea%22&f=false |title=Passport Series: Western Europe |isbn=978-1-4291-2255-9 |publisher=Lorenz Educational Press |year=2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\">{{cite web |last=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |title=Zealand |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/656125/Zealand |publisher=Britannica.com |accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref>  It also is a [[Provinces of Sweden|province]], [[Counties of Sweden|county]], [[Municipalities of Sweden|municipality]], and [[Church of Sweden|diocese]]. The province includes the islands of [[F\u00e5r\u00f6]] and [[Gotska Sand\u00f6n]] to the north, as well as the Karls\u00f6 Islands ([[Lilla Karls\u00f6|Lilla]] and [[Stora Karls\u00f6|Stora]]) to the west. The population is 58,595,<ref name=\"population\">[http://www.scb.se/hitta-statistik/statistik-efter-amne/befolkning/befolkningens-sammansattning/befolkningsstatistik/pong/tabell-och-diagram/helarsstatistik--forsamling-landskap-och-stad/folkmangd-i-landskapen-den-31-december-2017/ Statistics Sweden (as of December 31, 2017)]</ref> of which about 23,600 live in [[Visby]], the main town.<ref name=\"Gotlandisiffror\">{{cite web|title=Gotland i siffror, pdf|url=http://www.gotland.se/64224|website=www.gotland.se|publisher=Region Gotland|pages=65\u201367|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> The island of Gotland and the other areas of the province of Gotland make up less than one percent of Sweden's total land area.\n\nThe island's main sources of income are agriculture, food processing, tourism, information technology services, design, and some heavy industry such as concrete production from locally mined [[limestone]].<ref name=Fakta /> From a military viewpoint, it occupies a strategic location in the [[Baltic Sea|Baltic sea]]. As of 2018 the [[Gotland Regiment]] has been  re-raised and it is the first time since World War II that a new regiment has been established in Sweden.\n\n==Name==\n{{See|Name of the Goths}}\nThe name of Gotland is closely related to that of the [[Geats]] and [[Goths]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Strid |first1=Jan Paul |author-link1=Jan Paul Strid |date=January 2010 |editor1-last= |editor1-first= |editor1-link= |title=The Origin of the Goths from a Topolinguistic Perspective |script-title= |trans-title= |department= |journal=North-Western European Language Evolution |type= |series= |language= |edition= |publisher=[[John Benjamins Publishing Company]] |publication-date= |volume=58 |issue=59 |pages=443\u2013452 |nopp= |arxiv= |asin= |bibcode= |bibcode-access= |biorxiv= |citeseerx= |doi=10.1075/nowele.58-59.16str |doi-access= |issn= |jfm= |jstor= |jstor-access= |lccn= |mr= |oclc= |ol= |ol-access= |osti= |osti-access= |pmc= |pmid= |rfc= |ssrn= |zbl= |id= |layurl= |laysource= |laydate= |quote= |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n=== Prehistoric time to Viking Age ===\nThe island is the home of the [[Gutes]], and sites such as the [[Ajvide Settlement]] show that it has been occupied since [[prehistory]].<ref name=\"Outram\">Outram, A. K. 2006. [https://ore.exeter.ac.uk/repository/bitstream/handle/10036/23495/Distinguishing%20bone%20fat.PDF?sequence=1&isAllowed=y Distinguishing bone fat exploitation from other taphonomic processes: what caused the high level of bone fragmentation at the Middle Neolithic site of Ajvide, Gotland?], pp. 32-43. In Mulville, J and Outram, A (eds). ''The Zooarchaeology of Milk and Fats''. Oxford: Oxbow Books. {{open access}}</ref> A DNA study conducted on the 5,000-year-old skeletal remains of three Middle Neolithic seal hunters from Gotland showed that they were related to modern-day Finns, while a farmer from [[G\u00f6khem]] parish in [[V\u00e4sterg\u00f6tland]] on the mainland was found to be more closely related to modern-day Mediterraneans. This is consistent with the spread of agricultural peoples from the Middle East at about that time.<ref name=\"nature.com\">[http://www.nature.com/news/ancient-swedish-farmer-came-from-the-mediterranean-1.10541 DNA study published in nature.com on April 26, 2012.  Pontus Skoglund on prehistoric Gotlanders: ''\"The hunter-gatherers show the greatest similarity to modern-day Finns.\"'']</ref>\n\n[[File:U 614, Tors\u00e4tra.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Tors\u00e4tra runestone ([[Uppland Runic Inscription 614|U 614]]) raised in memory of one of the Swedish king's tribute collectors who fell ill and died during a trip to Gotland. [[Swedish History Museum]], Stockholm.]]\n[[Gutasaga]] contains legends of how the island was settled by [[\u00dej\u00e1lfi and R\u00f6skva|\u00deieluar]] and populated by his descendants. It also tells that a third of the population had to emigrate and settle in southern Europe, a tradition associated with the migration of the [[Goths]], whose name has the same origin as ''Gutes'', the native name of the people of the island. It later tells that the Gutes voluntarily submitted to the king of Sweden and asserts that the submission was based on mutual agreement, and notes the duties and obligations of the Swedish King and Bishop in relationship to Gotland.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gutagatan, based on Gannholm's 1992 edition|url=http://runeberg.org/gutasaga/|website=www.runeberg.org|publisher=Project Runeberg|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> According to some historians, it is therefore an effort not only to write down the history of Gotland, but also to assert Gotland's independence from Sweden.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Enderborg |first1=Bernt |title=Staten Gotland |url=http://www.guteinfo.com/scripts/utskrift.asp?id=1891&ant=0 |website=www.guteinfo.com |publisher=Guteinfo |accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nIt gives Awair Strabain as the name of the man who arranged the mutually beneficial agreement with the king of Sweden; the event would have taken place before the end of the 9th century, when [[Wulfstan of Hedeby]] reported that the island was subject to the Swedes:\n\n{{quotation |Then, after the [[Bornholm|land of the Burgundians]], we had on our left the lands that have been called from the earliest times [[Blekinge]]y, and [[M\u00f6re|Meore]], and [[\u00d6land|Eowland]], and Gotland, all which territory is subject to the [[Swedes (Germanic tribe)|Sweons]]; and Weonodland was all the way on our right, as far as [[Vistula|Weissel]]-mouth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/4076 |title=Discovery of Muscovy by Richard Hakluyt \u2013 Project Gutenberg |publisher=Gutenberg.org |date=1 May 2003 |accessdate=11 August 2010}}</ref>}}\n\nThe number of [[Arabs|Arab]] [[dirham]]s discovered on the island of Gotland alone is astoundingly high. In the various [[hoard]]s located around the island, there are more of these silver coins than at any other site in Western [[Eurasia]]. The total sum is almost as great as the number that has been unearthed in the entire [[Muslim]] world.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Johansson |first1=Marcus |last2=Jonsson |first2=Kenneth |title=Islamiska mynt |url=http://www.archaeology.su.se/polopoly_fs/1.55057.1321542315!/menu/standard/file/Johansson_Islamiska%20mynt.pdf |website=www.archeology.su.se |publisher=Numismatiska forskningsgruppen, Stockholms universitet. |date=1997 |page=2 |accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> These coins moved north through trade between [[Rus' people|Rus]] merchants and the [[Abbasid Caliphate]], along the [[Silver-Fur Road]], and the money made by Scandinavian merchants would help northern Europe, especially Viking Scandinavia and the [[Carolingian Empire]], as major commercial centers for the next several centuries.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vikingarnas historia|url=http://www.rosala-viking-centre.com/historik.htm|website=www.rosala-viking-centre.com|publisher=Rosala Viking center|accessdate=13 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214033201/http://www.rosala-viking-centre.com/historik.htm|archive-date=14 December 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Berezan' Runestone]], discovered in 1905 in Ukraine, was made by a [[Varangians|Varangian]] ([[Vikings|Viking]]) trader named Grani in memory of his [[f\u00e9lag|business partner]] Karl. It is assumed that they were from Gotland.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jansson |first1=Sven B. F. |title=The runes of Sweden |date=1962 |publisher=Norstedt |location=Stockholm |pages=3\u20134 |url=http://libris.kb.se/bib/613271 |accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==== Notable archaeological findings ====\n{{further|Spillings Hoard}}\n[[File:Spillings Silver Hoard 2 side.jpg|thumb|A part of the Spillings Hoard at Gotlands Museum.]]\nThe [[M\u00e4stermyr chest]], an important artefact from the [[Viking Age]], was found in Gotland.<ref>{{cite web |last1=\u00c5hlin |first1=Christer |title=Verktygskista fr\u00e5n M\u00e4stermyr |url=http://www.historiska.se/template/RelatedImagePopup.aspx?parent=19951&image=19962 |website=www.historiska.se |publisher=Historiska Museet |accessdate=5 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606220849/http://www.historiska.se/template/RelatedImagePopup.aspx?parent=19951&image=19962 |archive-date=6 June 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hellner |first1=Brynolf |title=Tidigare publikationer om M\u00e4stermyrfyndet |url=http://www.historicallocks.com/sv/site/historicallocks/Sakerhetsskap/Mastermyr-och-Oseberg/Tidigare-publikationer-om-Mastermyrfyndet/ |website=wwwhistoricallocks.com |publisher=Historical locks |accessdate=5 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606233413/http://www.historicallocks.com/sv/site/historicallocks/Sakerhetsskap/Mastermyr-och-Oseberg/Tidigare-publikationer-om-Mastermyrfyndet/ |archive-date=6 June 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 16{{nbsp}}July 1999, the world's largest Viking silver treasure, the [[Spillings Hoard]], was found in a field at Spillings farm northwest of [[Slite]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Spillingsskatten|url=http://www.historiska.se/utstallningar/tidigareutstallningar/2002/spillingsskatten/|website=www.historiska.se|publisher=Historiska Museet|accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref> The silver treasure was divided into two parts weighing a total of {{convert|67|kg|lb|abbr=on}} ({{convert|27|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and {{convert|40|kg|lb|abbr=on}}) and consisted mostly of coins, about 14,000, from foreign countries, mostly Islamic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Unikt mynt hittat i Spillingsskatten|url=http://www.hallekis.com/arkiv1/xx020629e.htm|website=www.hallekis.com|publisher=Hallekiskuriren|accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref> It also contained about {{convert|20|kg|lb|abbr=on}} of bronze objects along with numerous everyday objects such as nails, glass beads, parts of tools, pottery, iron bands and clasps. The treasure was found by using a metal detector, and the finders fee, given to the farmer who owned the land, was over 2&nbsp;million kronor (about US$308,000).<ref>{{cite book |editor=Ann-Marie Pettersson |title=Spillingsskatten: Gotland i vikingatidens v\u00e4rldshandel |date=2008 |publisher=L\u00e4nsmuseet p\u00e5 Gotland |location=Visby |isbn=978-91-88036-69-8 |url=http://libris.kb.se/bib/10907056 |accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref> The treasure was found almost by accident while filming a news report for [[TV4 (Sweden)|TV4]] about illegal treasure hunting on Gotland.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Str\u00f6m |first1=Jonas |title=V\u00e4rldens st\u00f6rsta vikingatida silverskatt |url=http://www.historiska.se/historia/manadensforemal/2002/mfjuni2002/ |website=www.historiska.se |publisher=Historiska museet |accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Middle Ages ===\n[[File:Tofta-Kyrka-S.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Tofta Church, Gotland|Tofta Church]], one of the island's many [[Churches on Gotland|distinctive, well-preserved medieval churches]].]]\nEarly on, Gotland became a commercial center, with the town of Visby the most important [[Hanseatic League|Hanseatic]] city in the Baltic Sea.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Yrwing |first1=Hugo |title=Visby \u2013 hansestad p\u00e5 Gotland |date=1986 |publisher=Gidlund |location=Stockholm |language=Swedish |isbn=91-7844-055-6 |url=http://libris.kb.se/bib/7668452 |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref> In late medieval times, the island had twenty district courts ([[thing (assembly)|tings]]), each represented by its elected judge at the island-ting, called ''landsting''. New laws were decided at the landsting, which also took other decisions regarding the island as a whole.<ref name=\"Tacitus\">{{cite web |last1=Martinsson |first1=\u00d6rjan |title=Gotland |url=http://www.tacitus.nu/svenskhistoria/land/gotland.htm |website=www.tacitus.nu |publisher=TACITUS.NU |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe city of Visby and rest of the island were governed separately, and a civil war caused by conflicts between the German merchants in Visby and the peasants they traded with in the countryside [[Treaty of Gotland (1288)|had to be put down]] by King [[Magnus III of Sweden]] in 1288.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sundberg |first1=Ulf |title=Svenska freder och stillest\u00e5nd 1249\u20131814 |date=1997 |publisher=Arte |location=Hargshamn |isbn=91-89080-01-7 |edition=1 |language=Swedish |url=http://libris.kb.se/bib/7777792 |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref> In 1361, [[Valdemar IV of Denmark|Valdemar Atterdag of Denmark]] invaded the island.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Westholm |first1=Gun |title=Visby 1361: Invasionen |date=2007 |publisher=Prisma |language=Swedish |location=Stockholm |isbn=978-91-518-4568-5 |url=http://libris.kb.se/bib/10415688 |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref> About 1,500 Gotlandic farmers were killed by the Danish invaders after massing for [[Battle of M\u00e4sterby|battle at M\u00e4sterby]].<ref name=Invasion>{{cite web|last1=Lingstr\u00f6m|first1=Allan|title=Invasionen-fakta och teorier|url=http://www.masterby1361.se/docs/faktaochteorier.htm|website=www.masterby1361.se|publisher=M\u00e4sterby1361|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> The [[Victual Brothers]] occupied the island in 1394 to set up a stronghold as a headquarters of their own in Visby. At last, Gotland became a [[fief]] of the [[Teutonic Knights]], awarded to them on the condition that they expel the piratical Victual Brothers from their fortified sanctuary.<ref name=Tacitus /> An invading army of Teutonic Knights conquered the island in 1398, destroying Visby and driving the Victual Brothers from Gotland. In 1409, Grand Master [[Ulrich von Jungingen]] of the Teutonic Knights guaranteed peace with the [[Kalmar Union]] of [[Scandinavia]] by selling the island of Gotland to Queen [[Margaret I of Denmark|Margaret of Denmark, Norway and Sweden]].<ref name=Tacitus />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible\" style=\"float:left; margin-right:1em;\"\n|+ Historical affiliations\n|-\n| {{flagicon image|COA family sv Magnus Ladul\u00e5s.svg}} Vassal of [[Sweden]] || 1285\u20131361\n|-\n| {{flag|Denmark}} || 1361\u20131394\n|-\n| [[Victual Brothers]] || 1394\u20131398\n|-\n| {{flagicon image|Insignia Germany Order Teutonic.svg}} [[Teutonic Order]] || 1398\u20131408\n|-\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of the Kalmar Union.svg}} [[Kalmar Union]] || 1408\u20131523\n|-\n| {{flag|Denmark}} || 1523\u20131645\n|-\n| {{flag|Sweden}} || 1645\u20131676\n|-\n| {{flag|Denmark}} || 1676\u20131679\n|-\n| {{flag|Sweden}} || 1679\u20131808\n|-\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of Russia.svg}} [[Russian Empire]] || 1808\n|-\n| {{flag|Sweden}}||1808\u2013present\n|}\n\nThe authority of the landsting was successively eroded after the island was occupied by the Teutonic Order, then sold to [[Eric of Pomerania]] and after 1449 ruled by [[Denmark|Danish]] governors.<ref name=Tacitus /> In late medieval times, the ting consisted of twelve representatives for the farmers, free-holders or tenants.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n=== Early modern period ===\n[[File:Gotlandold.png|thumb|upright|Sockens on Gotland. The sockens are written in small text, the bolder names are the names of the municipalities existing 1950\u20131970.]]\nSince the [[Second Treaty of Br\u00f6msebro (1645)|Treaty of Br\u00f6msebro]] in 1645, the island has remained under Swedish rule.<ref name=Tacitus /><ref>{{cite book |last=Englund |first=Peter |title=Ofreds\u00e5r |publisher=Atlantis |location=Stockholm |year=2003 |pages=368 and 394 |isbn=91-7486-349-5 |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 September 1806, the Swedish government offered sovereignty of Gotland to the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of St. John of Jerusalem]], who had been [[Mediterranean campaign of 1798#Malta|expelled]] from [[Malta]] in 1798, but the Order rejected the offer since it would have meant renouncing their claim to Malta. The Order never regained its territory, and eventually it reestablished itself in [[Rome]] as the [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stair Sainty |first1=Guy |title=From the loss of Malta to the modern era |url=http://www.chivalricorders.org/orders/smom/maltmod.htm |website=ChivalricOrders.org |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306192355/http://www.chivalricorders.org/orders/smom/maltmod.htm |archivedate=6 March 2012 |date=2000}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April 1808, during the [[Finnish War]] between Sweden and Russia, a Russian army landed on the southeastern shores of Gotland near [[Gr\u00f6tlingbo]]. Under command of [[Nikolai Bodisko|Nikolai Andreevich Bodisko]] 1,800 Russians took the city of [[Visby]] without any combat or engagement, and occupied the island. A Swedish naval force rescue expedition was sent from [[Karlskrona]] under the command of admiral [[Rudolf Cederstr\u00f6m]] with 2,000 men; the island was liberated and the Russians capitulated. Russian forces left the island on 18 May 1808.\n\n== Administration ==\nThe traditional [[provinces of Sweden]] serve no administrative or political purposes today, but are historical and cultural entities. In the case of Gotland, however, due to its insular position, the administrative [[counties of Sweden|county]] (''l\u00e4n''), [[Gotland County]], and the [[municipalities of Sweden|municipality]] (''kommun''), [[Gotland Municipality]], both cover the same territory as the province. Furthermore, the [[diocese of Visby]] is also congruent with the province.<ref>{{cite web|title=V\u00e4lkommen till Region Gotlands hemsida!|url=http://www.gotland.se/|website=www.gotland.se|publisher=Region Gotland|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=L\u00e4nsstyrelsen Gotlands l\u00e4n|url=http://www.lansstyrelsen.se/gotland/Sv/Pages/default.aspx|website=www.lansstyrelsen.se|publisher=L\u00e4nsstyrelsen Gotlands l\u00e4n|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Visby Stift|url=http://www.svenskakyrkan.se/visbystift|website=www.svenskakyrkan.se|publisher=Sveska Kyrkan|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> Gotland is traditionally divided into 92 [[socken]]s.<ref name=Gotlandisiffror /> On 1{{nbsp}}January 2016, they were all reconstituted into [[Registration districts in Sweden|Districts]], administrative areas with the same borders as the former sockens.<ref>{{cite web|title=F\u00f6rordning om district|trans-title=Regulation of districts|url=http://rkrattsdb.gov.se/SFSdoc/15/150493.PDF|date=17 June 2015|publisher=[[Ministry of Finance (Sweden)|Ministry of Finance]]|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Heraldry ==\n[[File:Flag of Gotland.svg|thumb|Unofficial flag of Gotland]]\nGotland was granted its arms in about 1560.<ref>Clara Nev\u00e9us, Bror jacques de W\u00e6rn: ''Ny svensk vapenbok'', 1992</ref> The [[coat of arms]] is represented with a ducal coronet. Blazon: \"Azure a ram statant Argent armed Or holding on a cross-staff of the same a banner Gules bordered and with five tails of the third.\" The county was granted the same coat of arms in 1936. The municipality, created in 1971, uses the same picture, but with other [[tincture (heraldry)|tinctures]].\n\nThe Gotlandic flag displays the Gotlandic coat of arms, white on red ground, known from the 13th century in the shape of the seal of the Gutnish Republic with the proud ram. It reads: \"Gutenses signo xpistus signatur in agno\".\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:Topographic map of Gotland.svg|thumb|Map of Gotland]]\n[[File:Baltic marine subdivisions and drainage basins.gif|thumb|The marine areas around Gotland, which lies between the numerals&nbsp;7&nbsp;and&nbsp;8, which, along with No.&nbsp;9, form the [[Gotland Basin]]]]\nGotland is Sweden's largest island, and it is the largest island fully encompassed by the [[Baltic Sea]] (with Denmark's [[Zealand]] at the Baltic's edge).<ref name=\"Renate\" /><ref name=\"Sailing\" /><ref name=\"Knowles\" /><ref name=\"Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\" /> With its total area of {{convert|3,183.7|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} the island of Gotland and the other areas of the province of Gotland make up 0.8% of Sweden's total land area.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gotland i siffror 2013 (\"Gotland in numbers 2013\")|url=http://www.gotland.se/64224|website=pdf|publisher=Region Gotland|accessdate=1 June 2014}}</ref> The province includes the small islands of F\u00e5r\u00f6 and Gotska Sand\u00f6n to the north, as well as the Karls\u00f6 Islands, (Lilla and Stora) to the west, which are even smaller. The island of Gotland has an area of {{convert|2,994|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}, whereas the province has {{convert|3,183.7|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} [{{convert|3,151|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} of land excluding the lakes and rivers].<ref>[http://www.scb.se/Pages/PublishingCalendarViewInfo____259923.aspx?PublObjId=10420 Statistisk \u00e5rsbok f\u00f6r Sverige 2009]</ref> The population is 57,221,<ref name=\"population\" /> of which about 23,600 live in Visby, the seat of the municipality as well as the capital of the county.<ref name=\"Gotlandisiffror\" /> About two-fifths of the island's population live in Visby.\n\nGotland is located about {{convert|90|km|mi|abbr=on}} east of the Swedish mainland and about {{convert|130|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the [[Baltic states]], [[Latvia]] being the nearest. Gotland is the name of the main island, but the adjacent islands are generally considered part of Gotland and the Gotlandic culture:\n\n* [[Furillen]]\n* [[F\u00e5r\u00f6]]\n* [[Gotska Sand\u00f6n]], a [[List of national parks of Sweden|National park of Sweden]]\n* The Karls\u00f6 Islands ([[Stora Karls\u00f6]] and [[Lilla Karls\u00f6]])\n* [[Lau, Gotland#Lau Islets|Laus holmar]]\n* Ytterholmen\n* [[\u00d6stergarnsholm]]\n\nThere are several shallow lakes located near the shores of the island. The biggest is [[Lake B\u00e4stetr\u00e4sk]], located near [[Fleringe]] in the northern part of Gotland.\n\nThe [[Hoburg Shoal]] [[bird reserve]] is situated on the southern tip of the island.<ref name=mpa>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mpatlas.org/mpa/sites/5804/ |title=MP Atlas; Hoburgs Bank Special Protection Areas (Birds Directive) |access-date=1 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923072513/http://www.mpatlas.org/mpa/sites/5804/ |archive-date=23 September 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe highest point of the island is [[Lojsta#Lojsta Moor|Lojsta Hed]] which stands {{convert|82|m|ft|abbr=on}} above sea level.\n\n=== Climate ===\nGotland has a semi-continental variety of a [[oceanic climate|marine climate]]. This results in larger seasonal differences than typical of marine climates in spite of it being surrounded by the Baltic Sea for large distances in all directions. This is due to strong continental winds travelling over the sea from surrounding great landmasses.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Visby, temperature 2002\u20132015, precipitation 1961\u20131990 (sunshine 2002\u20132014)\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan record high C = 10.2\n|Feb record high C = 12.2\n|Mar record high C = 18.6\n|Apr record high C = 25.2\n|May record high C = 27.7\n|Jun record high C = 31.4\n|Jul record high C = 33.7\n|Aug record high C = 31.8\n|Sep record high C = 29.0\n|Oct record high C = 20.0\n|Nov record high C = 13.5\n|Dec record high C = 12.5\n|year record high C = 33.7\n|Jan high C = 1.4\n|Feb high C = 1.2\n|Mar high C = 4.5\n|Apr high C = 10.0\n|May high C = 15.2\n|Jun high C = 18.8\n|Jul high C = 22.0\n|Aug high C = 21.3\n|Sep high C = 17.0\n|Oct high C = 10.9\n|Nov high C = 6.8\n|Dec high C = 3.5\n|year high C = 11.0\n|Jan mean C = -0.5\n|Feb mean C = -0.9\n|Mar mean C = 1.1\n|Apr mean C = 5.5\n|May mean C = 10.4\n|Jun mean C = 14.4\n|Jul mean C = 17.9\n|Aug mean C = 17.3\n|Sep mean C = 13.4\n|Oct mean C = 8.1\n|Nov mean C = 4.8\n|Dec mean C = 1.6\n|year mean C = 7.7\n|Jan low C = 