\n| coastline_footnotes = &nbsp;(including F\u00e5r\u00f6)\n| highest_mount    = Lojsta hed\n| elevation_m      = 82\n| country          = [[Sweden]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title     = County\n| country_admin_divisions           = [[Gotland County]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_1   = Municipality\n| country_admin_divisions_1         = [[Gotland Municipality]]\n| country_largest_city              = [[Visby]]\n| country_largest_city_population   = 23,600<ref name=\"Gotlandisiffror\" />\n| population       = 58,595<ref name=\"population\" />\n| population_as_of = 2017\n| density_km2      = 18.4\n| ethnic_groups    =\n| additional_info  =\n| module = \n{{Designation list\n| embed = yes\n| designation1 = Ramsar\n| designation1_offname = Gotland, east coast\n| designation1_date = 5 December 1974\n| designation1_number = 21<ref>{{Cite web|title=Gotland, east coast|website=[[Ramsar Convention|Ramsar]] Sites Information Service|url=https://rsis.ramsar.org/ris/21|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>}}\n}}\n\n'''Gotland''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0261|\u0252|t|l|\u0259|n|d}}; {{IPA-sv|\u02c8\u0261\u0254\u030ct\u02d0land|lang|sv-Gotland.ogg}};<ref>[http://sok.saol.se/pages/P296_M.jpg] [[Svenska Akademiens ordlista]], 6 February 2013</ref> older spellings include '''Gottland''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0261|\u0252|t|l|\u0259|n|d}} or '''Gothland''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0261|\u0252|\u03b8|l|\u0259|n|d}};<ref>[http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/gotland]</ref> ''Gutland'' in the [[Gutnish|local dialect]])<ref>{{cite web|title=Namnet Gotland|trans-title=The name Gotland|url=http://www.guteinfo.com/?id=1890|website=www.guteinfo.com|publisher=Guteinfo|accessdate=7 April 2015}}</ref> is Sweden's largest [[island]].<ref name=\"Renate\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AyIU6XIeDKwC&pg=PA178 |title=The Baltic Sea: new developments in national policies and international cooperation, Volume 1 |authors=Renate Platz\u00f6der, Philom\u00e8ne A. Verlaan |publisher=Martinus Nijhoff Publishers |year=1996}}</ref><ref name=\"Sailing\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T7-G4MRcvjwC&pg=PA147 |title=Sailing Directions, Baltic Sea |publisher=ProStar Publications |isbn=978-1-57785-759-4}}</ref><ref name=\"Knowles\">{{cite book |last=Knowles |first=Heather |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z25SYOLd_pIC&lpg=PA145&dq=%22the%20largest%20island%20in%20the%20baltic%20sea%22&pg=PA145#v=onepage&q=%22the%20largest%20island%20in%20the%20baltic%20sea%22&f=false |title=Passport Series: Western Europe |isbn=978-1-4291-2255-9 |publisher=Lorenz Educational Press |year=2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\">{{cite web |last=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |title=Zealand |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/656125/Zealand |publisher=Britannica.com |accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref>  It also is a [[Provinces of Sweden|province]], [[Counties of Sweden|county]], [[Municipalities of Sweden|municipality]], and [[Church of Sweden|diocese]]. The province includes the islands of [[F\u00e5r\u00f6]] and [[Gotska Sand\u00f6n]] to the north, as well as the Karls\u00f6 Islands ([[Lilla Karls\u00f6|Lilla]] and [[Stora Karls\u00f6|Stora]]) to the west. The population is 58,595,<ref name=\"population\">[http://www.scb.se/hitta-statistik/statistik-efter-amne/befolkning/befolkningens-sammansattning/befolkningsstatistik/pong/tabell-och-diagram/helarsstatistik--forsamling-landskap-och-stad/folkmangd-i-landskapen-den-31-december-2017/ Statistics Sweden (as of December 31, 2017)]</ref> of which about 23,600 live in [[Visby]], the main town.<ref name=\"Gotlandisiffror\">{{cite web|title=Gotland i siffror, pdf|url=http://www.gotland.se/64224|website=www.gotland.se|publisher=Region Gotland|pages=65\u201367|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> The island of Gotland and the other areas of the province of Gotland make up less than one percent of Sweden's total land area.\n\nThe island's main sources of income are agriculture, food processing, tourism, information technology services, design, and some heavy industry such as concrete production from locally mined [[limestone]].<ref name=Fakta /> From a military viewpoint, it occupies a strategic location in the [[Baltic Sea|Baltic sea]]. As of 2018 the [[Gotland Regiment]] has been  re-raised and it is the first time since World War II that a new regiment has been established in Sweden.\n\n==Name==\n{{See|Name of the Goths}}\nThe name of of Gotland is closely related to that of the [[Geats]] and [[Goths]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Strid |first1=Jan Paul |author-link1=Jan Paul Strid |date=January 2010 |editor1-last= |editor1-first= |editor1-link= |title=The Origin of the Goths from a Topolinguistic Perspective |script-title= |trans-title= |department= |journal=North-Western European Language Evolution |type= |series= |language= |edition= |publisher=[[John Benjamins Publishing Company]] |publication-date= |volume=58 |issue=59 |pages=443\u2013452 |nopp= |arxiv= |asin= |bibcode= |bibcode-access= |biorxiv= |citeseerx= |doi=10.1075/nowele.58-59.16str |doi-access= |issn= |jfm= |jstor= |jstor-access= |lccn= |mr= |oclc= |ol= |ol-access= |osti= |osti-access= |pmc= |pmid= |rfc= |ssrn= |zbl= |id= |layurl= |laysource= |laydate= |quote= |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n=== Prehistoric time to Viking Age ===\nThe island is the home of the [[Gutes]], and sites such as the [[Ajvide Settlement]] show that it has been occupied since [[prehistory]].<ref name=\"Outram\">Outram, A. K. 2006. [https://ore.exeter.ac.uk/repository/bitstream/handle/10036/23495/Distinguishing%20bone%20fat.PDF?sequence=1&isAllowed=y Distinguishing bone fat exploitation from other taphonomic processes: what caused the high level of bone fragmentation at the Middle Neolithic site of Ajvide, Gotland?], pp. 32-43. In Mulville, J and Outram, A (eds). ''The Zooarchaeology of Milk and Fats''. Oxford: Oxbow Books. {{open access}}</ref> A DNA study conducted on the 5,000-year-old skeletal remains of three Middle Neolithic seal hunters from Gotland showed that they were related to modern-day Finns, while a farmer from [[G\u00f6khem]] parish in [[V\u00e4sterg\u00f6tland]] on the mainland was found to be more closely related to modern-day Mediterraneans. This is consistent with the spread of agricultural peoples from the Middle East at about that time.<ref name=\"nature.com\">[http://www.nature.com/news/ancient-swedish-farmer-came-from-the-mediterranean-1.10541 DNA study published in nature.com on April 26, 2012.  Pontus Skoglund on prehistoric Gotlanders: ''\"The hunter-gatherers show the greatest similarity to modern-day Finns.\"'']</ref>\n\n[[File:U 614, Tors\u00e4tra.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Tors\u00e4tra runestone ([[Uppland Runic Inscription 614|U 614]]) raised in memory of one of the Swedish king's tribute collectors who fell ill and died during a trip to Gotland. [[Swedish History Museum]], Stockholm.]]\n[[Gutasaga]] contains legends of how the island was settled by [[\u00dej\u00e1lfi and R\u00f6skva|\u00deieluar]] and populated by his descendants. It also tells that a third of the population had to emigrate and settle in southern Europe, a tradition associated with the migration of the [[Goths]], whose name has the same origin as ''Gutes'', the native name of the people of the island. It later tells that the Gutes voluntarily submitted to the king of Sweden and asserts that the submission was based on mutual agreement, and notes the duties and obligations of the Swedish King and Bishop in relationship to Gotland.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gutagatan, based on Gannholm's 1992 edition|url=http://runeberg.org/gutasaga/|website=www.runeberg.org|publisher=Project Runeberg|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> According to some historians, it is therefore an effort not only to write down the history of Gotland, but also to assert Gotland's independence from Sweden.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Enderborg |first1=Bernt |title=Staten Gotland |url=http://www.guteinfo.com/scripts/utskrift.asp?id=1891&ant=0 |website=www.guteinfo.com |publisher=Guteinfo |accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nIt gives Awair Strabain as the name of the man who arranged the mutually beneficial agreement with the king of Sweden; the event would have taken place before the end of the 9th century, when [[Wulfstan of Hedeby]] reported that the island was subject to the Swedes:\n\n{{quotation |Then, after the [[Bornholm|land of the Burgundians]], we had on our left the lands that have been called from the earliest times [[Blekinge]]y, and [[M\u00f6re|Meore]], and [[\u00d6land|Eowland]], and Gotland, all which territory is subject to the [[Swedes (Germanic tribe)|Sweons]]; and Weonodland was all the way on our right, as far as [[Vistula|Weissel]]-mouth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/etext/4076 |title=Discovery of Muscovy by Richard Hakluyt \u2013 Project Gutenberg |publisher=Gutenberg.org |date=1 May 2003 |accessdate=11 August 2010}}</ref>}}\n\nThe number of [[Arabs|Arab]] [[dirham]]s discovered on the island of Gotland alone is astoundingly high. In the various [[hoard]]s located around the island, there are more of these silver coins than at any other site in Western [[Eurasia]]. The total sum is almost as great as the number that has been unearthed in the entire [[Muslim]] world.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Johansson |first1=Marcus |last2=Jonsson |first2=Kenneth |title=Islamiska mynt |url=http://www.archaeology.su.se/polopoly_fs/1.55057.1321542315!/menu/standard/file/Johansson_Islamiska%20mynt.pdf |website=www.archeology.su.se |publisher=Numismatiska forskningsgruppen, Stockholms universitet. |date=1997 |page=2 |accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> These coins moved north through trade between [[Rus' people|Rus]] merchants and the [[Abbasid Caliphate]], along the [[Silver-Fur Road]], and the money made by Scandinavian merchants would help northern Europe, especially Viking Scandinavia and the [[Carolingian Empire]], as major commercial centers for the next several centuries.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vikingarnas historia|url=http://www.rosala-viking-centre.com/historik.htm|website=www.rosala-viking-centre.com|publisher=Rosala Viking center|accessdate=13 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214033201/http://www.rosala-viking-centre.com/historik.htm|archive-date=14 December 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Berezan' Runestone]], discovered in 1905 in Ukraine, was made by a [[Varangians|Varangian]] ([[Vikings|Viking]]) trader named Grani in memory of his [[f\u00e9lag|business partner]] Karl. It is assumed that they were from Gotland.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jansson |first1=Sven B. F. |title=The runes of Sweden |date=1962 |publisher=Norstedt |location=Stockholm |pages=3\u20134 |url=http://libris.kb.se/bib/613271 |accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==== Notable archaeological findings ====\n{{further|Spillings Hoard}}\n[[File:Spillings Silver Hoard 2 side.jpg|thumb|A part of the Spillings Hoard at Gotlands Museum.]]\nThe [[M\u00e4stermyr chest]], an important artefact from the [[Viking Age]], was found in Gotland.<ref>{{cite web |last1=\u00c5hlin |first1=Christer |title=Verktygskista fr\u00e5n M\u00e4stermyr |url=http://www.historiska.se/template/RelatedImagePopup.aspx?parent=19951&image=19962 |website=www.historiska.se |publisher=Historiska Museet |accessdate=5 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606220849/http://www.historiska.se/template/RelatedImagePopup.aspx?parent=19951&image=19962 |archive-date=6 June 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hellner |first1=Brynolf |title=Tidigare publikationer om M\u00e4stermyrfyndet |url=http://www.historicallocks.com/sv/site/historicallocks/Sakerhetsskap/Mastermyr-och-Oseberg/Tidigare-publikationer-om-Mastermyrfyndet/ |website=wwwhistoricallocks.com |publisher=Historical locks |accessdate=5 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606233413/http://www.historicallocks.com/sv/site/historicallocks/Sakerhetsskap/Mastermyr-och-Oseberg/Tidigare-publikationer-om-Mastermyrfyndet/ |archive-date=6 June 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 16{{nbsp}}July 1999, the world's largest Viking silver treasure, the [[Spillings Hoard]], was found in a field at Spillings farm northwest of [[Slite]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Spillingsskatten|url=http://www.historiska.se/utstallningar/tidigareutstallningar/2002/spillingsskatten/|website=www.historiska.se|publisher=Historiska Museet|accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref> The silver treasure was divided into two parts weighing a total of {{convert|67|kg|lb|abbr=on}} ({{convert|27|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and {{convert|40|kg|lb|abbr=on}}) and consisted mostly of coins, about 14,000, from foreign countries, mostly Islamic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Unikt mynt hittat i Spillingsskatten|url=http://www.hallekis.com/arkiv1/xx020629e.htm|website=www.hallekis.com|publisher=Hallekiskuriren|accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref> It also contained about {{convert|20|kg|lb|abbr=on}} of bronze objects along with numerous everyday objects such as nails, glass beads, parts of tools, pottery, iron bands and clasps. The treasure was found by using a metal detector, and the finders fee, given to the farmer who owned the land, was over 2&nbsp;million kronor (about US$308,000).<ref>{{cite book |editor=Ann-Marie Pettersson |title=Spillingsskatten: Gotland i vikingatidens v\u00e4rldshandel |date=2008 |publisher=L\u00e4nsmuseet p\u00e5 Gotland |location=Visby |isbn=978-91-88036-69-8 |url=http://libris.kb.se/bib/10907056 |accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref> The treasure was found almost by accident while filming a news report for [[TV4 (Sweden)|TV4]] about illegal treasure hunting on Gotland.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Str\u00f6m |first1=Jonas |title=V\u00e4rldens st\u00f6rsta vikingatida silverskatt |url=http://www.historiska.se/historia/manadensforemal/2002/mfjuni2002/ |website=www.historiska.se |publisher=Historiska museet |accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Middle Ages ===\n[[File:Tofta-Kyrka-S.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Tofta Church, Gotland|Tofta Church]], one of the island's many [[Churches on Gotland|distinctive, well-preserved medieval churches]].]]\nEarly on, Gotland became a commercial center, with the town of Visby the most important [[Hanseatic League|Hanseatic]] city in the Baltic Sea.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Yrwing |first1=Hugo |title=Visby \u2013 hansestad p\u00e5 Gotland |date=1986 |publisher=Gidlund |location=Stockholm |language=Swedish |isbn=91-7844-055-6 |url=http://libris.kb.se/bib/7668452 |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref> In late medieval times, the island had twenty district courts ([[thing (assembly)|tings]]), each represented by its elected judge at the island-ting, called ''landsting''. New laws were decided at the landsting, which also took other decisions regarding the island as a whole.<ref name=\"Tacitus\">{{cite web |last1=Martinsson |first1=\u00d6rjan |title=Gotland |url=http://www.tacitus.nu/svenskhistoria/land/gotland.htm |website=www.tacitus.nu |publisher=TACITUS.NU |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe city of Visby and rest of the island were governed separately, and a civil war caused by conflicts between the German merchants in Visby and the peasants they traded with in the countryside [[Treaty of Gotland (1288)|had to be put down]] by King [[Magnus III of Sweden]] in 1288.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sundberg |first1=Ulf |title=Svenska freder och stillest\u00e5nd 1249\u20131814 |date=1997 |publisher=Arte |location=Hargshamn |isbn=91-89080-01-7 |edition=1 |language=Swedish |url=http://libris.kb.se/bib/7777792 |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref> In 1361, [[Valdemar IV of Denmark|Valdemar Atterdag of Denmark]] invaded the island.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Westholm |first1=Gun |title=Visby 1361: Invasionen |date=2007 |publisher=Prisma |language=Swedish |location=Stockholm |isbn=978-91-518-4568-5 |url=http://libris.kb.se/bib/10415688 |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref> About 1,500 Gotlandic farmers were killed by the Danish invaders after massing for [[Battle of M\u00e4sterby|battle at M\u00e4sterby]].<ref name=Invasion>{{cite web|last1=Lingstr\u00f6m|first1=Allan|title=Invasionen-fakta och teorier|url=http://www.masterby1361.se/docs/faktaochteorier.htm|website=www.masterby1361.se|publisher=M\u00e4sterby1361|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> The [[Victual Brothers]] occupied the island in 1394 to set up a stronghold as a headquarters of their own in Visby. At last, Gotland became a [[fief]] of the [[Teutonic Knights]], awarded to them on the condition that they expel the piratical Victual Brothers from their fortified sanctuary.<ref name=Tacitus /> An invading army of Teutonic Knights conquered the island in 1398, destroying Visby and driving the Victual Brothers from Gotland. In 1409, Grand Master [[Ulrich von Jungingen]] of the Teutonic Knights guaranteed peace with the [[Kalmar Union]] of [[Scandinavia]] by selling the island of Gotland to Queen [[Margaret I of Denmark|Margaret of Denmark, Norway and Sweden]].<ref name=Tacitus />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible\" style=\"float:left; margin-right:1em;\"\n|+ Historical affiliations\n|-\n| {{flagicon image|COA family sv Magnus Ladul\u00e5s.svg}} Vassal of [[Sweden]] || 1285\u20131361\n|-\n| {{flag|Denmark}} || 1361\u20131394\n|-\n| [[Victual Brothers]] || 1394\u20131398\n|-\n| {{flagicon image|Insignia Germany Order Teutonic.svg}} [[Teutonic Order]] || 1398\u20131408\n|-\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of the Kalmar Union.svg}} [[Kalmar Union]] || 1408\u20131523\n|-\n| {{flag|Denmark}} || 1523\u20131645\n|-\n| {{flag|Sweden}} || 1645\u20131676\n|-\n| {{flag|Denmark}} || 1676\u20131679\n|-\n| {{flag|Sweden}} || 1679\u20131808\n|-\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of Russia.svg}} [[Russian Empire]] || 1808\n|-\n| {{flag|Sweden}}||1808\u2013present\n|}\n\nThe authority of the landsting was successively eroded after the island was occupied by the Teutonic Order, then sold to [[Eric of Pomerania]] and after 1449 ruled by [[Denmark|Danish]] governors.<ref name=Tacitus /> In late medieval times, the ting consisted of twelve representatives for the farmers, free-holders or tenants.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n=== Early modern period ===\n[[File:Gotlandold.png|thumb|upright|Sockens on Gotland. The sockens are written in small text, the bolder names are the names of the municipalities existing 1950\u20131970.]]\nSince the [[Second Treaty of Br\u00f6msebro (1645)|Treaty of Br\u00f6msebro]] in 1645, the island has remained under Swedish rule.<ref name=Tacitus /><ref>{{cite book |last=Englund |first=Peter |title=Ofreds\u00e5r |publisher=Atlantis |location=Stockholm |year=2003 |pages=368 and 394 |isbn=91-7486-349-5 |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 September 1806, the Swedish government offered sovereignty of Gotland to the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of St. John of Jerusalem]], who had been [[Mediterranean campaign of 1798#Malta|expelled]] from [[Malta]] in 1798, but the Order rejected the offer since it would have meant renouncing their claim to Malta. The Order never regained its territory, and eventually it reestablished itself in [[Rome]] as the [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stair Sainty |first1=Guy |title=From the loss of Malta to the modern era |url=http://www.chivalricorders.org/orders/smom/maltmod.htm |website=ChivalricOrders.org |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306192355/http://www.chivalricorders.org/orders/smom/maltmod.htm |archivedate=6 March 2012 |date=2000}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April 1808, during the [[Finnish War]] between Sweden and Russia, a Russian army landed on the southeastern shores of Gotland near [[Gr\u00f6tlingbo]]. Under command of [[Nikolai Bodisko|Nikolai Andreevich Bodisko]] 1,800 Russians took the city of [[Visby]] without any combat or engagement, and occupied the island. A Swedish naval force rescue expedition was sent from [[Karlskrona]] under the command of admiral [[Rudolf Cederstr\u00f6m]] with 2,000 men; the island was liberated and the Russians capitulated. Russian forces left the island on 18 May 1808.\n\n== Administration ==\nThe traditional [[provinces of Sweden]] serve no administrative or political purposes today, but are historical and cultural entities. In the case of Gotland, however, due to its insular position, the administrative [[counties of Sweden|county]] (''l\u00e4n''), [[Gotland County]], and the [[municipalities of Sweden|municipality]] (''kommun''), [[Gotland Municipality]], both cover the same territory as the province. Furthermore, the [[diocese of Visby]] is also congruent with the province.<ref>{{cite web|title=V\u00e4lkommen till Region Gotlands hemsida!|url=http://www.gotland.se/|website=www.gotland.se|publisher=Region Gotland|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=L\u00e4nsstyrelsen Gotlands l\u00e4n|url=http://www.lansstyrelsen.se/gotland/Sv/Pages/default.aspx|website=www.lansstyrelsen.se|publisher=L\u00e4nsstyrelsen Gotlands l\u00e4n|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Visby Stift|url=http://www.svenskakyrkan.se/visbystift|website=www.svenskakyrkan.se|publisher=Sveska Kyrkan|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> Gotland is traditionally divided into 92 [[socken]]s.<ref name=Gotlandisiffror /> On 1{{nbsp}}January 2016, they were all reconstituted into [[Registration districts in Sweden|Districts]], administrative areas with the same borders as the former sockens.<ref>{{cite web|title=F\u00f6rordning om district|trans-title=Regulation of districts|url=http://rkrattsdb.gov.se/SFSdoc/15/150493.PDF|date=17 June 2015|publisher=[[Ministry of Finance (Sweden)|Ministry of Finance]]|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Heraldry ==\n[[File:Flag of Gotland.svg|thumb|Unofficial flag of Gotland]]\nGotland was granted its arms in about 1560.<ref>Clara Nev\u00e9us, Bror jacques de W\u00e6rn: ''Ny svensk vapenbok'', 1992</ref> The [[coat of arms]] is represented with a ducal coronet. Blazon: \"Azure a ram statant Argent armed Or holding on a cross-staff of the same a banner Gules bordered and with five tails of the third.\" The county was granted the same coat of arms in 1936. The municipality, created in 1971, uses the same picture, but with other [[tincture (heraldry)|tinctures]].\n\nThe Gotlandic flag displays the Gotlandic coat of arms, white on red ground, known from the 13th century in the shape of the seal of the Gutnish Republic with the proud ram. It reads: \"Gutenses signo xpistus signatur in agno\".\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:Topographic map of Gotland.svg|thumb|Map of Gotland]]\n[[File:Baltic marine subdivisions and drainage basins.gif|thumb|The marine areas around Gotland, which lies between the numerals&nbsp;7&nbsp;and&nbsp;8, which, along with No.&nbsp;9, form the [[Gotland Basin]]]]\nGotland is Sweden's largest island, and it is the largest island fully encompassed by the [[Baltic Sea]] (with Denmark's [[Zealand]] at the Baltic's edge).<ref name=\"Renate\" /><ref name=\"Sailing\" /><ref name=\"Knowles\" /><ref name=\"Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica\" /> With its total area of {{convert|3,183.7|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} the island of Gotland and the other areas of the province of Gotland make up 0.8% of Sweden's total land area.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gotland i siffror 2013 (\"Gotland in numbers 2013\")|url=http://www.gotland.se/64224|website=pdf|publisher=Region Gotland|accessdate=1 June 2014}}</ref> The province includes the small islands of F\u00e5r\u00f6 and Gotska Sand\u00f6n to the north, as well as the Karls\u00f6 Islands, (Lilla and Stora) to the west, which are even smaller. The island of Gotland has an area of {{convert|2,994|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}, whereas the province has {{convert|3,183.7|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} [{{convert|3,151|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} of land excluding the lakes and rivers].<ref>[http://www.scb.se/Pages/PublishingCalendarViewInfo____259923.aspx?PublObjId=10420 Statistisk \u00e5rsbok f\u00f6r Sverige 2009]</ref> The population is 57,221,<ref name=\"population\" /> of which about 23,600 live in Visby, the seat of the municipality as well as the capital of the county.<ref name=\"Gotlandisiffror\" /> About two-fifths of the island's population live in Visby.\n\nGotland is located about {{convert|90|km|mi|abbr=on}} east of the Swedish mainland and about {{convert|130|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the [[Baltic states]], [[Latvia]] being the nearest. Gotland is the name of the main island, but the adjacent islands are generally considered part of Gotland and the Gotlandic culture:\n\n* [[Furillen]]\n* [[F\u00e5r\u00f6]]\n* [[Gotska Sand\u00f6n]], a [[List of national parks of Sweden|National park of Sweden]]\n* The Karls\u00f6 Islands ([[Stora Karls\u00f6]] and [[Lilla Karls\u00f6]])\n* [[Lau, Gotland#Lau Islets|Laus holmar]]\n* Ytterholmen\n* [[\u00d6stergarnsholm]]\n\nThere are several shallow lakes located near the shores of the island. The biggest is [[Lake B\u00e4stetr\u00e4sk]], located near [[Fleringe]] in the northern part of Gotland.\n\nThe [[Hoburg Shoal]] [[bird reserve]] is situated on the southern tip of the island.<ref name=mpa>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mpatlas.org/mpa/sites/5804/ |title=MP Atlas; Hoburgs Bank Special Protection Areas (Birds Directive) |access-date=1 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923072513/http://www.mpatlas.org/mpa/sites/5804/ |archive-date=23 September 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe highest point of the island is [[Lojsta#Lojsta Moor|Lojsta Hed]] which stands {{convert|82|m|ft|abbr=on}} above sea level.\n\n=== Climate ===\nGotland has a semi-continental variety of a [[oceanic climate|marine climate]]. This results in larger seasonal differences than typical of marine climates in spite of it being surrounded by the Baltic Sea for large distances in all directions. This is due to strong continental winds travelling over the sea from surrounding great landmasses.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Visby, temperature 2002\u20132015, precipitation 1961\u20131990 (sunshine 2002\u20132014)\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan record high C = 10.2\n|Feb record high C = 12.2\n|Mar record high C = 18.6\n|Apr record high C = 25.2\n|May record high C = 27.7\n|Jun record high C = 31.4\n|Jul record high C = 33.7\n|Aug record high C = 31.8\n|Sep record high C = 29.0\n|Oct record high C = 20.0\n|Nov record high C = 13.5\n|Dec record high C = 12.5\n|year record high C = 33.7\n|Jan high C = 1.4\n|Feb high C = 1.2\n|Mar high C = 4.5\n|Apr high C = 10.0\n|May high C = 15.2\n|Jun high C = 18.8\n|Jul high C = 22.0\n|Aug high C = 21.3\n|Sep high C = 17.0\n|Oct high C = 10.9\n|Nov high C = 6.8\n|Dec high C = 3.5\n|year high C = 11.0\n|Jan mean C = -0.5\n|Feb mean C = -0.9\n|Mar mean C = 1.1\n|Apr mean C = 5.5\n|May mean C = 10.4\n|Jun mean C = 14.4\n|Jul mean C = 17.9\n|Aug mean C = 17.3\n|Sep mean C = 13.4\n|Oct mean C = 8.1\n|Nov mean C = 4.8\n|Dec mean C = 1.6\n|year mean C = 7.7\n|Jan low C = -2.5\n|Feb low C = -3.0\n|Mar low C = -2.3\n|Apr low C = 1.0\n|May low C = 5.7\n|Jun low C = 9.9\n|Jul low C = 13.8\n|Aug low C = 13.2\n|Sep low C = 9.9\n|Oct low C = 5.3\n|Nov low C = 2.8\n|Dec low C = -0.3\n|year low C = 4.4\n|Jan record low C = -25.0\n|Feb record low C = -25.4\n|Mar record low C = -23.5\n|Apr record low C = -12.7\n|May record low C = -6.9\n|Jun record low C = -1.0\n|Jul record low C = 2.9\n|Aug record low C = 1.1\n|Sep record low C = -2.9\n|Oct record low C = -6.0\n|Nov record low C = -11.5\n|Dec record low C = -22.2\n|year record low C = -25.4\n|rain colour = green\n|Jan rain mm = 53\n|Feb rain mm = 29\n|Mar rain mm = 35\n|Apr rain mm = 29\n|May rain mm = 29\n|Jun rain mm = 30\n|Jul rain mm = 50\n|Aug rain mm = 49\n|Sep rain mm = 58\n|Oct rain mm = 48\n|Nov rain mm = 58\n|Dec rain mm = 54\n|Jan sun = 37\n|Feb sun = 64\n|Mar sun = 174\n|Apr sun = 255\n|May sun = 310\n|Jun sun = 329\n|Jul sun = 308\n|Aug sun = 254\n|Sep sun = 202\n|Oct sun = 102\n|Nov sun = 41\n|Dec sun = 31\n|year sun = 2107\n|source 1=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smhi.se/klimatdata/meteorologi/temperatur/2.1240|title=Monthly & Yearly Statistics |publisher=SMHI|accessdate=3 March 2016 }}</ref>\n|source 2=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.smhi.se/met/climate/time_series/month_year/normal_1961_1990/SMHI_month_year_normal_61_90_precipitation_mm.txt|title=Precipitation normals 1961\u20131990|publisher=SMHI|accessdate=3 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928213811/http://data.smhi.se/met/climate/time_series/month_year/normal_1961_1990/SMHI_month_year_normal_61_90_precipitation_mm.txt|archive-date=28 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n\n=== Geology ===\n{{Main|Geology of Gotland}}\n[[File:Rauks (3881539849).jpg|thumb|[[Rauk]]s at Langhammars, F\u00e5r\u00f6]]\n[[File:Gotland-reef hg.jpg|thumb|A Silurian [[reef]] complex]]\nGotland is made up of a sequence of [[sedimentary rock]]s of a [[Silurian]] age, dipping to the south-east.\nThe main Silurian succession of [[limestone]]s and [[shale]]s comprises thirteen units spanning {{convert|200|to|500|m|abbr=on}} of stratigraphic thickness, being thickest in the south, and overlies a {{convert|75|to|125|m|abbr=on}} thick [[Ordovician]] sequence.<ref name=Laufeld1974>{{cite book |last=Laufeld |first=S. |year=1974 |title=Silurian Chitinozoa from Gotland |publisher=Universitetsforlaget |series=Fossils and Strata |issue=5 }}</ref>\n\nIt was deposited in a shallow, hot and salty sea, on the edge of an equatorial continent.<ref>Creer 1973</ref> The water depth never exceeded {{convert|175|to|200|m|abbr=on}},<ref>{{citation |authors=Jane Gray, S. Laufield, and Arthur J. Boucot |year=1974 |title=Silurian trilete spores and spore tetrads from Gotland: their implications for land plant evolution |journal=Science |volume=185 |issue=4147 |pages=260\u2013263 |doi=10.1126/science.185.4147.260 |pmid=17812053}}</ref> and became shallower over time as [[Reef knoll|bioherm]] detritus, and terrestrial sediments, filled the basin. Reef growth started in the [[Llandovery]], when the sea was {{convert|50|to|100|m|abbr=on}}, and reefs continued to dominate the sedimentary record.<ref name=Laufeld1974 /> Some sandstones are present in the youngest rocks towards the south of the island, which represent sand bars deposited very close to the shore line.<ref name=Long1993>{{cite journal |last=Long |first=D.G.F. |year=1993 |journal=Geologiska F\u00f6reningens i Stockholms F\u00f6rhandlingar (GFF) |title=The Burgsvik beds, an Upper Silurian storm generated sand ridge complex in southern Gotland |volume=115 |pages=299\u2013309 |issn=0016-786X |issue=4 |doi=10.1080/11035899309453917 }}</ref>\n\nThe lime rocks have been weathered into characteristic [[karst]]ic [[List of rock formations|rock formations]] known as [[rauk]]s. Fossils, mainly of [[crinoid]]s, [[rugosa|rugose]] [[coral]]s and [[brachiopod]]s, are abundant throughout the island; pal\u00e6o-[[Stack (geology)|sea-stacks]] are preserved in places.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Sven |last=Laufeld |first2=Anders |last2=Martinsson |title=Reefs and ultrashallow environments. Guidebook to the field excursions in the Silurian of Gotland |journal=Project Ecostratigraphy Plenary Meeting |date=22\u201328 August 1981}}</ref>\n\n== Economy ==\n\nThe island's main sources of income are agriculture along with food processing, tourism, IT solutions, design and some heavy industry such as concrete production from locally mined [[limestone]]. Most of Gotland's economy is based on small scale production.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gibson |first=Mimmi |title=Gotl\u00e4ndskt n\u00e4ringsliv |url=http://www.lansstyrelsen.se/gotland/Sv/om-lansstyrelsen/om-lanet/Pages/gotland_naringsliv.aspx |work=Website |publisher=L\u00e4nsstyrelsen Gotland |accessdate=31 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026150519/http://www.lansstyrelsen.se/gotland/Sv/om-lansstyrelsen/om-lanet/Pages/gotland_naringsliv.aspx |archive-date=26 October 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nIn 2012, there were over 7,500 registered companies on Gotland.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gotland i siffror 2013 (\"Gotland in numbers 2013\")|url=http://www.gotland.se/64224|work=pdf|p=18|publisher=Region Gotland|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref> 1,500 of these had more than one employee.<ref name=Fakta>{{cite web|title=Fakta om Gotland|url=http://www.lansstyrelsen.se/gotland/Sv/om-lansstyrelsen/om-lanet/Pages/gotland_fakta_.aspx|work=Website|publisher=L\u00e4nsstyrelsen Gotland|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref> Gotland has the world's northernmost established vineyard and winery, located in [[Hablingbo]].<ref>{{cite web|title=D\u00e4rf\u00f6r s\u00e4ljs Gute ving\u00e5rd|url=http://www.helagotland.se/ekonomi/darforsaljsgute-vingard-12204708.aspx|date=3 November 2015|website=www.helagotland.se|publisher=Gotlands Tidningar|accessdate=9 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pappinen|first1=Lauri|title=English information|url=http://gutevingard.se/om-oss/english-information/|website=www.gutevingard.se|publisher=Gute Ving\u00e5rd AB|accessdate=9 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n! colspan=2 | Gotlands largest employers in 2015<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gotland.se/64224 |publisher=Region Gotland |title=GOTLAND I SIFFROR |trans-title=GOTLAND IN NUMBERS |page=19 |date=2016 |access-date=14 September 2016 |language=Swedish |quote=Number of permanent employees stationed on the island}}</ref>\n|-\n| '''Company''' || '''Employees'''\n|-\n| [[Gotland Municipality|Region Gotland]] (\"Gotland Municipality\") || 5700\n|-\n| [[Svenska Spel|AB Svenska Spel]] (\"Swedish Games\")|| 360\n|-\n| PayEx (\"Payment solutions\")|| 310\n|-\n| [[Destination Gotland]] (Ferries and accommodations) || 300\n|-\n| [[Swedish Social Insurance Agency|F\u00f6rs\u00e4kringskassan]] (\"Swedish Social Insurance Agency\") || 280\n|-\n| Samhall AB (Providing employment for disabled persons) || 260\n|-\n| Cementa (Concrete industry) || 240\n|-\n| [[Campus Gotland|Uppsala University Campus Gotland]] (\"Gotland university\") || 180\n|-\n| [[Swedish Police Authority]] (\"Police\") || 180\n|-\n| Gotlands Energientreprenad AB (Electrical company) || 150\n|-\n| COOP Gotland ek f\u00f6r. (Swedish consumers co-operative) || 150\n|-\n| [[ICA AB|ICA MAXI]]/Brukets Livs AB (Hypermarket) || 130\n|-\n| Gotlands Slagteri AB (Food company) || 130\n|-\n| L\u00e4nsstyrelsen i Gotlands l\u00e4n (County administrative board) || 120\n|-\n| Gotlands Hemstj\u00e4nster AB (Personal assistance) || 120\n|-\n| [[Swedish Tax Agency|Skatteverket]] (\"Swedish Tax Agency\")|| 110\n|-\n| [[Swedish National Heritage Board|Riksantikvarie\u00e4mbetet]] (\"Swedish National Heritage Board\") || 110\n|-\n| Wisby Assistans AB (Personal assistance) || 110\n|-\n| Gotlands Bilfrakt AB (Freight company) || 100\n|-\n| [[PostNord Sverige]] (\"Swedish Post\") || 90\n|}\n\n== Military ==\n{{Main|Military on Gotland}}\n[[File:Bunker from WWII, nearby Brucebo, Gotland, Sweden.jpeg|thumb|World War II era ''kulsprutebunker'' (machine gun bunker) located near Brucebo, Gotland County]]\nGotland occupies a strategic location in the Baltic sea from a defence viewpoint. The Swedish government decided in March 2015 to begin reestablishing a permanent military presence on Gotland, starting with an initial 150 troop garrison,<ref name=\"newgarrison\">{{cite web |last=Milne |first=Richard |title=Sweden sends troops to Baltic island amid Russia tensions |url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/660d038c-c8bc-11e4-8617-00144feab7de.html#axzz3UD7oACNX |publisher=ft.com |accessdate=12 March 2015}}</ref> consisting primarily of elements from the [[Swedish Army]]. It has been reported that the bulk of this initial garrison will make up a new motorised rifle battalion,<ref name=riflebat>[http://www.helagotland.se/nyheter/in-utrikes/gotland-far-permanent-militar-styrka-10812484.aspx Gotland f\u00e5r permanent milit\u00e4r styrka] helagotland.se {{in lang|sv}}</ref> alternatively referred to in other reports as a \"modular-structured rapid response Army battalion\". A later report claimed that plans were at an advanced stage for a [[Swedish Air Force#Helicopter units|support helicopter squadron]] and an Air Force \"fast response Gripen jet squadron\" to also be based on the island to support the new garrison and further reinforce the defences.<ref name=defNewsA26>{{cite web |last=O'Dwyer |first=Gerard |title=Sweden Invests In Naval Capacity, Baltic Sea Ops |url=http://www.defensenews.com/story/defense/2015/03/20/sweden-invests-in-naval-capacity-and-baltic-sea/25093841/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20150404123206/http://www.defensenews.com/story/defense/2015/03/20/sweden-invests-in-naval-capacity-and-baltic-sea/25093841/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 April 2015 |publisher=DefenseNews |date=20 March 2015 |accessdate=22 March 2015 }}</ref> Prior to the disbandment of the original garrison, there had been a continuous Swedish military presence on Gotland in one form or another, for nearly 200 years.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Olsson |first1=K |title=Milit\u00e4rbef\u00e4let p\u00e5 Gotland |trans-title=Military command on Gotland |url=http://www.tjelvar.se/milbef/mb.htm |website=www.tjelvar.se |publisher=Gotlands Milit\u00e4rhistoria och Gotlands Trupper |accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter the standing down of the original garrison, a battalion of the [[Home Guard (Sweden)|Swedish Home Guard]] is based on Gotland for emergencies as part of the Eastern Military Region (''MR E''). The unit, ''32:a Gotlandsbataljonen'' (the 32nd Gotland battalion), acts as a reserve component of the [[Swedish Amphibious Corps]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Gotlandsbataljonen|url=http://www.forsvarsmakten.se/sv/organisation/amfibieregementet-amf-1/insatsforband/gotlandsbataljonen/|website=www.forsvarsmakten.se|publisher=[[Swedish Armed Forces]]|accessdate=14 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150715195532/http://www.forsvarsmakten.se/sv/organisation/amfibieregementet-amf-1/insatsforband/gotlandsbataljonen/|archive-date=15 July 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Among the residual [[war reserve stock]]s reported to be still in storage on Gotland in March 2015, were 14 tanks<ref>{{cite web |last1=Braw |first1=Elisabeth |title=Gotland Island, the Baltic Sea's Weak Link |url=http://www.worldaffairsjournal.org/blog/elisabeth-braw/gotland-island-baltic-seas-weak-link |website=www.worldaffairsjournal.org |publisher=[[World Affairs]] |accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> ([[Stridsvagn 122]]s) at the ''Tofta skjutf\u00e4lt'' (the [[Tofta, Gotland|Tofta]] firing range),<ref>{{cite web|title=Stridsvagnar \u00e5ter p\u00e5 Gotland|trans-title=Tanks return to Gotland|url=http://www.forsvarsmakten.se/sv/aktuellt/2013/10/stridsvagnar-ater-pa-gotland/|website=www.forsvarsmakten.se|publisher=[[Swedish Armed Forces]]|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=novembertraining>{{cite web|title=I 19 tar \u00f6ver p\u00e5 Gotland|trans-title=In 19 takes over on Gotland|url=http://www.forsvarsmakten.se/sv/aktuellt/2014/11/i-19-tar-over-pa-gotland/|publisher=[[Swedish Armed Forces]]|accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> but without any crews or dedicated maintenance personnel assigned to them.<ref name=tankwoes>{{cite web |last1=Kadhammar |first1=Peter |title=Blir det krig f\u00e5r arm\u00e9n k\u00f6pa mat p\u00e5 Ica Maxi |trans-title=If the war comes, the army will have to buy their food at Ica Maxi |url=http://www.aftonbladet.se/nyheter/kolumnister/peterkadhammar/article16258122.ab |website=www.aftonbladet.se |publisher=[[Aftonbladet]] |accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:CV9040 3.jpg|thumb|left|A 2005 photo of 4 IFVs ([[Combat Vehicle 90|Stridsfordon 90]]) during an exercise at ''Tofta skjutf\u00e4lt'']]\nGotland currently has no local air defence capability.<ref name=Tjelvar1 /> Despite its importance as a naval base in the past,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Olsson |first1=K |title=Gotlands Marindistrikt \u2013 Visbyavdelningen (Vba) \u2013 1931\u20131956 |trans-title=Gotland Navy District \u2013 Visby section \u2013 1931\u20131956 |url=http://www.tjelvar.se/marinen/marinen.htm |website=www.tjelvar.se |publisher=Gotlands Milit\u00e4rhistoria och Gotlands Trupper |accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> {{As of|2004|lc=y}}, there are no naval units based out of Gotland.<ref name=Tjelvar1>{{cite web |last1=Olsson |first1=K |title=Milit\u00e4rbef\u00e4let p\u00e5 Gotland |url=http://www.tjelvar.se/milbef/mb.htm |website=www.tjelvar.se |publisher=Gotlands Milit\u00e4rhistoria och Gotlands Trupper |accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> The Tofta firing range itself (also known as the Tofta Tank firing range), is a military training ground which is located {{convert|8|km|mi|abbr=on}} south of Visby. Another less common name for the range is the Toftasj\u00f6n firing range. Tracing its origins back to 1898, {{As of|2008|lc=y}} the range extended over {{convert|2,700|acre|km2|abbr=on}}. It was a major training and storage facility for the Gotland garrison during its existence, and was still occasionally used for training by various elements of the [[Swedish Armed Forces|Armed Forces]] since the garrison was shut down in 2005. However, from the second half of 2014 onwards, there has been a marked increase in the use of the range, especially by armored units (mostly company sized),<ref name=novembertraining /> as tensions in Northeastern Europe have escalated. At least one of the buildings on the range, the former tank [[Backshop|repair shop]], is currently owned by a private company ([[Peab]]), with the military renting back the top floor for its own use.<ref name=tankwoes /> \nWhen not used by the military, a number of cultural and sports events have been held at the range, one of the most notable being the [[Gotland Grand National]], the world's largest [[enduro]] race.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gottfridsson |first1=Thomas |title=GGN firar 30 \u00e5r med rekordantal |trans-title=Record breaking number of participants celebrates 30 years of GNN |url=http://www.helagotland.se/start/ggn-firar-30-ar-med-rekordantal-8961037.aspx |website=www.helagotland.se |publisher=HelaGotland |accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> As of 2018, Gotland has received a lot more attention military-wise and has seen a much larger spending on the military. As of 2018, the [[Gotland Regiment]] has been re-raised and is the first time since World War II that a new regiment has been established in Sweden.\n\n== Tourism ==\n[[File:Norsta Aurar at F\u00e5r\u00f6, Gotland in August 2014.jpg|thumb|Norsta Aurar beach on [[F\u00e5r\u00f6]]]]\nThe first modern day tourists came to Gotland during the 19th century and were known as \"bathers\".<ref name=Kulturen>{{cite book |last=Jonsson |first=Marita |title=V\u00e4gen till kulturen p\u00e5 Gotland |year=1987 |series=Gotl\u00e4ndskt arkiv, 0434-2429; 59(1987) |publisher=Gotlands fornsal |location=Visby |isbn=91-971048-0-9 |url=http://libris.kb.se/bib/7793296}}</ref> Gotland became very popular with socialites at the time through [[Princess Eugenie of Sweden and Norway|Princess Eugenie]] who lived in [[V\u00e4sterhejde]], in the west part of the island from the 1860s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ljugarn, historia|url=http://www.ljugarn.com/Default.aspx?ID=2437&MenID=5363|work=Website|publisher=Ljuvliga Ljugarn|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=Turisthistoria>{{cite web|title=Turisthistoria|url=http://www.lansstyrelsen.se/gotland/Sv/om-lansstyrelsen/om-lanet/Pages/gotland_turist.aspx|work=Website|publisher=L\u00e4nsstyrelsen Gotland|accessdate=31 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026141739/http://www.lansstyrelsen.se/gotland/Sv/om-lansstyrelsen/om-lanet/Pages/gotland_turist.aspx|archive-date=26 October 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nWhen a new law ensuring two weeks vacation for all employees in Sweden was passed in 1938, camping became a popular pastime among the Swedes, and in 1955, Gotland was visited by 80,000 people.<ref name=Turisthistoria /> In the 1970s mostly young people were attracted to Gotland. Since 2010 the island has become a more versatile vacation spot visited by people from all over the world, in all manner of ways.<ref name=Turisthistoria />\n\nIn 2001 it was the fifth largest tourist destination in Sweden based on the total number of guest nights.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gotland popul\u00e4rt turistm\u00e5l|url=http://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=94&artikel=62066|work=Website|publisher=Sveriges Radio|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref> Gotland is usually the part of Sweden which receives the most hours of sunlight during a year with Visby statistically the location with the most sunshine in Sweden.<ref>{{cite web |last=Sj\u00f6gren |first=Helena |title=Solkrig p\u00e5g\u00e5r mellan Karlskrona och Visby |url=http://www.expressen.se/kvp/solkrig-pagar-mellan-karlskrona-och-visby/ |work=Website/Newspaper |publisher=Expressen & SMHI |accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref> In 2007 approximately 750,000 people visited Gotland.<ref name=\"Fakta\" />\n\nIn 1996, for the first time, ferries between Gotland and mainland Sweden carried more than 1&nbsp;million passengers in a year. In 2007, the number of passengers exceeded 1.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fritz |first=Staffan |title=Passagerare nr 1500000 |url=http://www.helagotland.se/nyheter/artikel.aspx?ArticleId=2952349 |work=Website/Newspaper |publisher=Helagotland |accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref> In 2012, the ferries had 1,590,271 passengers and the airlines 327,255 passengers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gotland i siffror 2013 (\"Gotland in numbers 2013\")|url=http://www.gotland.se/64224|work=pdf|p=27|publisher=Region Gotland|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | <small>Number of tourists from top five countries in 2012</small><ref>{{cite web|title=Gotland i siffror 2013 (\"Gotland in numbers 2013\")|url=http://www.gotland.se/64224|work=pdf|p=24|publisher=Region Gotland|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flagicon|GER}} [[Germany]] || 31,664<ref name=Visitors>These numbers do not include visitors arriving by cruise ship. See section \"Cruise ships\".</ref>\n|-\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Norway]] || 16,350<ref name=Visitors />\n|-\n| {{flagicon|FIN}} [[Finland]] || 13,620<ref name=Visitors />\n|-\n| {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Denmark]] || 12,743<ref name=Visitors />\n|-\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[United States]] || 2,983<ref name=Visitors />\n|-\n| colspan=2 | <small>Based on the number of commercial guest nights at hotels, cabins, hostels, camping and private lodgings.</small>\n|}\n\n=== Cruise ships and new pier ===\n[[File:20190702 CMP kryssningshamn Visby Serenade of the Seas (48179968497).jpg|thumb|''[[Serenade of the Seas]]'' at the pier in the cruise ship harbor, 2019]]\nThe main port of call on Gotland is Visby. The city is visited by a number of cruise ships every year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Klint |first1=Kerstin |title=St\u00f6rre kryssningsfartyg till Visby |url=http://www.gotland.net/resa/arkiv/storre-kryssningsfartyg-till-visby |website=www.gotland.net |publisher=Visit Gotland |accessdate=2 June 2014}}</ref><ref>Visitors on these ships are not included in the statistics in the section above since they come to Gotland in ships owned by other shipping companies than Destination Gotland, and these visitors only disembark during the day and do not use the accommodation available on Gotland.</ref> About 40 cruise lines frequent the Baltic sea with Visby as one of their destinations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stenberg |first1=Johan |title=Bara 69 kryssningsfartyg till Visby |url=http://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=94&artikel=3596314 |accessdate=2 June 2014 |work=Website/Radio programme |agency=Sveriges Radio |publisher=P4 Gotland |date=31 March 2010}}</ref>  In 2005, 147 ships docked at Visby, in 2010 the number was 69.<ref name=Sweco>{{cite web|title=Att ang\u00f6ra en kaj eller passera en \u00f6, pdf|url=http://www.gotland.se/76453|website=www.gotland.se|publisher=Sweco Eurofutures AB|accessdate=2 June 2014}}</ref> In 2014, 62 ships are scheduled to visit Visby.<ref name=Port>{{cite web |last1=Wahlberg |first1=Lars |title=Cruise Calls 2014, Port of Visby, pdf |url=http://www.gotland.se/71028 |website=www.gotland.se |publisher=Port of Visby, Teknikf\u00f6rvaltningen, Hamnavdelningen, Region Gotland |accessdate=2 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606210027/http://www.gotland.se/71028 |archive-date=6 June 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The decrease in visiting ships is due to the fact that the modern cruise ships are too large to enter Visby harbor.<ref name=Sweco /> Ships must anchor a fair distance from shore whereupon passengers are shuttled to shore in small boats, which is not possible during bad weather.<ref name=Krysskaj>{{cite news |last1=Staflin |first1=Mona |last2=Pettersson |first2=Mats |title=Kryssningskaj kan ge 130 miljoner |url=http://www.helagotland.se/nyheter/artikel.aspx?articleid=9067561 |accessdate=2 June 2014 |work=Newspaper/website |agency=Helagotland |publisher=Gotlands Allehanda |date=18 November 2013}}</ref> In 2007, the first proposition for building a new pier at Visby harbor, large enough to serve the modern cruise ships, was made.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wesley |first1=Stefan |title=Planer f\u00f6r en kryssningskaj i Visby |url=http://www.gotland.se/36226 |website=www.gotland.se |publisher=Region Gotland |accessdate=2 June 2014}}</ref> In 2011, the matter of the new pier was discussed in the [[Riksdag]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Engelhart |first1=Christer |title=Motion 2011/12:T416 Kryssningskaj i Visby |url=http://www.riksdagen.se/sv/Dokument-Lagar/Forslag/Motioner/Kryssningskaj-i-Visby_GZ02T416/?text=true |website=www.riksdagen.se |publisher=Sveriges Riksdag |accessdate=2 June 2014}}</ref> and in 2012 research and planning for the pier began.<ref name=Sweco /> In January 2014 a letter of intent for building a new cruise pier in Visby harbor was signed by [[Gotland Municipality|Region Gotland]] and Copenhagen Malm\u00f6 Port (CMP). The pier is scheduled to be finished in 2018. The estimated cost is 250&nbsp;million [[Swedish krona|crowns]] (about US$38.52&nbsp;million).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Andersson |first1=Lars |title=Ny kryssningskaj i Visby |url=http://www.sjofartstidningen.se/ny-kryssningskaj-visby/ |accessdate=2 June 2014 |work=Website/Newspaper |publisher=Sj\u00f6fartstidningen |date=29 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bringmark |first1=Karsten |title=CMP f\u00f6rhandlar om kryssningskaj i Visby |url=http://www.skanskan.se/article/20140325/MALMO/140329730/-/cmp-forhandlar-om-kryssningskaj-i-visby |accessdate=2 June 2014 |work=Website/Newspaper |publisher=Sk\u00e5nskan |date=25 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n[[File:Visby ringmur \u00f6stra delen norrut.jpg|thumb|The eastern part of the Visby City Wall]]\nA number of stones with [[Grooves (archaeology)|grooves]] exist on Gotland. Archaeologists interpret these grooves as traces of an unknown industrial process in the [[High Middle Ages]]. There are approximately 3,700 grinding grooves, of which about 750 occur in the solid limestone outcrop and the rest in other rock formations. The latter often consist of hard rocks such as granite or gneiss, but also soft rocks such as sandstone occur.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gibson |first1=Olov |title=Gotlands slipsk\u00e5ror: sp\u00e5r av friktionsbromsar hos v\u00e4derkvarnar? |journal=Fornv\u00e4nnen |date=2013 |volume=108 |issue=2 |pages=130\u2013133 |url=http://kulturarvsdata.se/raa/fornvannen/html/2013_130 |accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> Grinding grooves are also found in Sk\u00e5ne, in southern Sweden and in Finland. Astronomer G\u00f6ran Henriksson dates a number of these grinding grooves to the Stone Age, from c. 3300 BCE to c. 2000 BCE, based on astronomical alignments,<ref name=\"henriksson\">{{cite journal |last=Henriksson |first=G\u00f6ran |journal=[[Fornv\u00e4nnen]] |title=Astronomisk tolkning av slipsk\u00e5ror p\u00e5 Gotland |year=1983 |url=http://fornvannen.se/pdf/1980talet/1983_021.pdf |publisher=[[Royal Swedish Academy of Letters, History and Antiquities]]}}</ref> although his methodology has been heavily criticized.<ref name=\"lindstrom_roslund\">{{cite journal |last=Lindstr\u00f6m |first=Jonathan |last2=Roslund |first2=Curt |journal=Folkvett |publisher=Vetenskap och Folkbildning |url=http://www.vof.se/folkvett/ar-2000/nr-3-4/goran-henrikssons-nonsensforskning |title=G\u00f6ran Henrikssons nonsensforskning |year=2000}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Havor Ring Replica.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Replica of gold [[torc]] from [[Havor Hoard]]]]\n[[File:Sacrificial scene on Hammars - Valknut.png|left|upright|thumb|The [[valknut]] symbol has its most discovered examples on Gotland]]\nThe Medieval town of Visby has been entered as a site of the [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site|World heritage]] programme. An impressive feature of Visby is the fortress wall that surrounds the old city, dating from the 13th century.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hanseatic Town of Visby|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/731|website=www.whc.unesco.org|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage List|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe inhabitants of Gotland traditionally spoke their own language, known as [[Old Gutnish]]. Today however, that language has become a Swedish dialect known as [[Gutnish]]. In the 13th century, a work containing the laws of the island, called \"the Gotlandic law\" (Gutalagen), was published in Old Gutnish, as well as the [[Gutasaga]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Olsson |first1=K |title=Gutalagen p\u00e5 svenska |url=http://www.tjelvar.se/varia/24-4.htm |website=www.tjelvar.se |publisher=Gotlands Milit\u00e4rhistoria och Gotlands Trupper |accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nGotland is noted for its 94 [[List of churches on Gotland|Medieval churches]],<ref>{{cite book |last=Andr\u00e9n |first=Anders |title=Det medeltida Gotland: En arkeologisk guidebook |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r4h2BgAAQBAJ&dq |publisher=Svenska Historiska Media F\u00f6rlag AB |date=2015 |volume=8 |series=Det medeltida |isbn=9187031310}}</ref> most of which are restored and in active use. These churches exhibit two major styles of architecture: [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] and [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]]. The older churches were constructed in the Romanesque style from 1150\u20131250. The newer churches were constructed in the Gothic architectural style that prevailed from about 1250\u20131400. The oldest painting inside one of the churches on Gotland stretches as far back in time as the 12th century.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lagerl\u00f6f |first1=Erland |last2=Svahnstr\u00f6m |first2=Gunnar |title=Gotlands kyrkor: en v\u00e4gledning |date=1973 |language=Swedish |publisher=Rab\u00e9n & Sj\u00f6gren |location=Stockholm |isbn=91-29-41035-5 |edition=2. omarb o ut\u00f6k. uppl. |url=http://libris.kb.se/bib/7232718 |accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nTraditional games of skill like [[Kubb]], [[P\u00e4rk]], and [[Varpa]] are played on Gotland. They are part of what has become called \"Gutniska Lekar\", and are performed preferably on the Midsummer's Eve celebration on the island, but also throughout the summer months. The games have widespread renown; some of them are played by people as far away as in the United States.<ref name=Stanga />\n\nThe knotwork design subsequently named the \"[[Valknut]]\" has the most attested historic instances on [[picture stone]]s in Gotland, which include being on both the [[Stora Hammars stones|Stora Hammars I]] and the [[T\u00e4ngelg\u00e5rda stone]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Valknut, triskele, Hrungnir's hj\u00e4rta|url=http://www.guteinfo.com/?id=3616|website=www.guteinfo.com|publisher=Guteinfo|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref>\nGotland also has a rich heritage of folklore, including myths about the [[bysen]], ''[[Di sma undar jordi]]'', Hoburgsgubben and the [[Martebo lights]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Saga|url=http://www.guteinfo.com/?avd=59&ord=Saga|website=www.guteinfo.com|publisher=Guteinfo|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wallin |first1=Inga-Lill |title=Marteboljuset |url=http://www.ufo.se/fakta/artiklar/martebo.shtml |website=www.ufo.se |publisher=UFO Sverige |accessdate=13 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100106052523/http://www.ufo.se/fakta/artiklar/martebo.shtml |archivedate=6 January 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nGotland gives its name to the traditional farmhouse ale [[Gotlandsdricka]], a turbid beer with much in common with Finnish [[sahti]], and related beers from the [[Baltic states]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Dricku|url=http://www.guteinfo.com/?id=113|website=www.guteinfo.com|publisher=Guteinfo|accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\n{{Main|List of people of Gotland}}\nThere are a number of notable people born or living on Gotland, or in other major ways associated with the island.<ref name=\"noted\">{{cite web |last1=Pettersson |first1=Mats |title=Ber\u00f6mda gotl\u00e4nningar |trans-title=Notable Gotlanders|url=https://www.gotland.net/sv/se-gora/arkiv/beromda-gotlanningar |website=www.gotland.net |date=9 December 2011|publisher=Gotlands Media AB |accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Dukes and Duchesses of Gotland ==\n[[File:Princess Leonore May 2016.jpg|thumb|125px|[[Princess Leonore, Duchess of Gotland]], 2014]]\n{{Main|Duke of Gotland}}\n* [[Prince Oscar Bernadotte|Prince Oscar]] 1859\u20131888 (lost title)\n* [[Princess Leonore, Duchess of Gotland|Princess Leonore]] 2014\u2013\n\n== Sport ==\n=== Events ===\n\n* Gotland competes in the biennial [[International Island Games Association|Island Games]], which it hosted in [[1999 Island Games|1999]] and [[2017 Island Games|2017]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Gotland \u2013 Member profile|url=http://www.islandgames.net/member_profile_12352.html|website=www.islandgames.net|publisher=INternational Island Games Association|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://islandgames2017.com/ |title=The Official 2017 Island Games website |access-date=10 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210155727/http://islandgames2017.com/ |archive-date=10 February 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Round Gotland Race]]-sailing event (\"\u00c5F Offshore Race\") starting at Stockholm, around the island of Gotland and back.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u00c5F Offshore Race|url=http://www.ksss.se/AFOR/|website=www.ksss.se|publisher=Royal Swedish Yacht Club|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Gotland Grand National]] (GGN) is an annual [[enduro]] race on Gotland. GGN is a part of the Swedish ''enduroklassikern'' (enduro classics, R\u00e4nnesl\u00e4ttsloppet, St\u00e5ngebroslaget and Gotland Grand National). GNN is  the world's largest enduro race.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gotland Grand national|url=http://www.nordicsportevent.se/evenemang/gotland-grand-national|website=www.nordicsportevent.se|publisher=Nordic sport & event|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=V\u00e4rldens st\u00f6rsta endurot\u00e4vling g\u00e5r av stapeln|url=http://www.tv4.se/sport/klipp/v%C3%A4rldens-st%C3%B6rsta-endurot%C3%A4vling-g%C3%A5r-av-stapeln-2479179|website=www.tv4.se|publisher=Tv 4, Sweden|accessdate=8 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714225700/http://www.tv4.se/sport/klipp/v%C3%A4rldens-st%C3%B6rsta-endurot%C3%A4vling-g%C3%A5r-av-stapeln-2479179|archive-date=14 July 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[St\u00e5nga Games]] are annual games for Gotlandic sports. The games are held during five days each summer in [[St\u00e5nga]]. The games are unofficially called \"the Gotland Olympic Games\". Some of the sports at the St\u00e5nga Games are [[p\u00e4rk]], [[varpa]] and [[caber toss]].<ref name=Stanga>{{cite web|title=St\u00e5ngsspelen|url=http://www.stangaspelen.com/|website=www.stangaspelen.com|publisher=F\u00f6reningen Gutnisk Idrott (FGI)|accessdate=8 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104085210/http://stangaspelen.com/|archive-date=4 January 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Organizations ===\n[[File:Paerk1.JPG|thumb|upright|P\u00e4rk at St\u00e5ngaspelen in 2006]]\nIn 2012, there were 171 registered sports organizations  on Gotland.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gotland i siffror 2013 (\"Gotland in numbers 2013\")|url=http://www.gotland.se/64224|website=pdf|page=41|publisher=Region Gotland|accessdate=1 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nGotland has two senior women's sport teams playing in the first tiers: [[basketball]] team [[Visby Ladies Basket Club]] (in [[Basketligan dam]]) and [[floorball]] team [[Endre IF]] (in the [[Swedish Super League (women's floorball)|Swedish Super League]]).<ref name=\"Teams in Basketligan dam\">{{cite web |url=http://iof1.idrottonline.se/SvenskaBasketbollforbundet/Basketligandam/Lag/ |title=Teams in Basketligan dam |publisher=[[Swedish Basketball Federation]] |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Teams in the Swedish Super League\">{{cite web |url=http://www.innebandy.se/sv/undersidor/ssl-dam/ |title=Women's Swedish Super League |publisher=[[Swedish Floorball Federation]] |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref> Visby Ladies won the Swedish Championship in 2005.<ref name=\"Visby Ladies 2005 Swedish Championship win\">{{cite web |url=http://www.guteinfo.com/?id=3012 |title=Visby Ladies svenska m\u00e4stare i basket 2005 |publisher=guteinfo.com |language=Swedish |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nFootball in the province is administered by [[Gotlands Fotbollf\u00f6rbund]]. The leading football club is [[FC Gute]], playing in the fourth-tier league [[Swedish Football Division 2|Division 2]] {{As of|2014|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gotlands idrottsf\u00f6rbund|url=http://iof4.idrottonline.se/Riksidrottsforbundet/Distrikt/GotlandsIdrottsforbund/|website=www.gotsport.se|publisher=Gotlands idrottsf\u00f6rbund|accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n''[[The Long Ships]]'', or ''Red Orm'' (original title: ''R\u00f6de Orm''), a best-selling Swedish novel written by [[Frans G. Bengtsson]], contains a vivid description of Gotland in the Viking Age. A section of the book is devoted to a Viking ship setting out to Russia, stopping on its way at Gotland and engaging a pilot from the island who plays an important part in their voyage. Gotlanders of the Viking era are depicted as city people, more sophisticated and cosmopolitan than other Scandinavians of their time, and proud of their knowledge and skills.\n\n[[Naomi Mitchison]], in her autobiographic book \"''You may well ask''\", relates an experience during a walking tour in Sweden: \"Over in Gotland I walked again, further than I would have if I had realized that the milestones were in [[Scandinavian mile|old Swedish miles]], so that my disappointing three-mile walk along the cold sea edge under the strange ancient fortifications was really fifteen English miles [24&nbsp;km]\".<ref>[[Naomi Mitchison]],\nYou may well ask\", London, 1979, Part I, Chap 7.</ref>\n\nThe crime novels of [[Mari Jungstedt]], featuring Detective Superintendent Anders Knutas, are set on Gotland.\n\nIn the ''[[Battlefield Vietnam]]'' video game [[Mod (video gaming)|modification]] ''Invasion Gotland'', the [[Soviet Armed Forces|Soviet Union]] invades Gotland in 1977.\n\nFor the 1989 Studio Ghibli film, ''[[Kiki's Delivery Service]]'', by Hayao Miyazaki, he and other illustrators spent time in Gotland in preparation for animation.\n\n== Astronomy ==\n[[File:Gotland-galgen hg.jpg|120px|thumb|The night sky at the old gallows, Visby, Gotland]]\n{{Main|List of Gotland-related asteroids}}\nA number of [[asteroid]]s in the [[Asteroid belt|main-belt]] are named after places on Gotland or Gotlanders, such as [[10795 Babben]], [[3250 Martebo]] and [[7545 Smakl\u00f6sa]]. Most of them have been named by Swedish [[astronomer]] [[Claes-Ingvar Lagerkvist]], a summer resident on Gotland. All the Gotlandic names are vividly described in NASA's [[JPL Small-Body Database]] in connection to each asteroid.<ref name=\"astro\">{{cite web|last1=Lagerkvist|first1=Claes-Ingvar|author-link1=Claes-Ingvar Lagerkvist|last2=Hahn|first2=Gerhard|title=Bl\u00e5gula asteroider|trans-title=Blue-yellow asteroids|date=3 March 2011|url=http://www.popularastronomi.se/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/2008-4_asteroider.pdfdate=2008|issue=4|website=www.popularastronomi.se|publisher=Popul\u00e4r Astronomi|accessdate=25 June 2016}}{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"sprak\">{{cite web|last1=Joelsson|first1=Johan|title=Vem d\u00f6per stj\u00e4rnorna?|trans-title=Who is naming the stars?|url=http://spraktidningen.se/artiklar/2014/12/vem-doper-stjarnorna|date=2014|website=www.spraktidningen.se|publisher=Spr\u00e5ktidningen|accessdate=25 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Div col|colwidth=18em}}\n*[[Cold War II]]\n*[[Danes]]\n*[[Danes (Germanic tribe)]]\n*[[Geats]]\n*[[Germanic peoples]]\n*[[Gothic alphabet]]\n*[[Gothic language]]\n*[[Gotland National Conscription]]\n*[[HVDC Gotland]]\n*[[Kvenland]]\n*[[List of church ruins on Gotland]]\n*[[List of churches on Gotland]]\n*[[Norsemen]]\n*[[Old Norse]]\n*[[Proto-Norse language]]\n*[[Scandza]]\n*[[Sweden during World War II]]\n*[[Sweden proper]]\n*[[Vavle]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\nThere are over 8,700 titles about Gotland in the [[National Library of Sweden]] on line database [[LIBRIS]]. About 560 of the books are in English. See: [http://libris.kb.se/hitlist?d=libris&q=gotland&f=simp&spell=true&hist=true&p=1 LIBRIS].\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n{{Commons category|Gotland}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Gotland}}\n* {{cite EB1911|wstitle=Gotland |volume=12 |short=x}}\n* {{cite NIE|wstitle=Gotland|year=1905 |short=x}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130921165827/http://gotland.se/1353 ''Gotland, facts and statistics 2013'', pdf, Gotland County.] {{in lang|en}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150402121431/http://www.gotlandsresor.se/en/english/about-gotland/chronicle Important years in Gotland' 